VALUES
(20, 17, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'a brother is born for adversity', 34, 65, 'theology', 'Role of Suffering', 'Many scholars believe this verse underscores the theological concept that familial relationships are designed to support one another during hardships. This notion is reflected in Galatians 6:2, which encourages believers to bear one another''s burdens. Such insights affirm the belief that God uses relationships to provide strength and comfort in adversity.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Galatians 6:2", "description": "Encouragement to support one another."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'A friend loveth at all times', 0, 28, 'question', 'Nature of Friendship', 'Reflecting on this truth, what actions demonstrate your commitment to being a friend ''at all times''? How can you embody this kind of unwavering support in your relationships, particularly when facing adversity?', 'heart.text.square', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'a brother is born for adversity', 34, 65, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Adversity''', 'עָצֶב (’āṣeb, H6093) - sorrow, trouble, or adversity. This Hebrew term suggests a depth of struggle that brings forth resilience and growth. Understanding the weight of ''adversity'' in this context highlights the importance of strong familial ties in navigating life''s challenges.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H6093", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term for adversity."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'striketh hands', 28, 42, 'connection', 'Covenantal Agreements', 'The phrase ''striketh hands'' can be connected to Proverbs 6:1, which warns against becoming surety for a friend. This highlights the importance of understanding the weight of commitments made in friendship. In the ancient Near Eastern context, striking hands often symbolized sealing an agreement, suggesting that one must exercise wisdom before entering into binding commitments.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 6:1", "description": "This verse warns against becoming a guarantor for someone else''s debts."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'void of understanding', 6, 27, 'theology', 'Value of Wisdom', 'This passage suggests that lacking understanding leads to poor decisions, particularly in financial matters. Many scholars believe that the Book of Proverbs emphasizes the necessity of wisdom for a righteous life. Such understanding is not merely intellectual but requires a deep engagement with God’s ways, leading to discernment in all areas of life.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Proverbs 4:7", "description": "This verse states that wisdom is the principal thing; therefore, get wisdom."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'becometh surety', 48, 63, 'greek', 'Understanding Surety', 'The term ''surety'' in this context can be connected to the Hebrew word עָרוּב (ʿārv, H6148) - pledge, guarantee. This reflects the biblical understanding of entering into obligations or commitments that bind one party to another, emphasizing the need for wisdom before engaging in such arrangements.', 'character.book.closed', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H6148", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term related to surety."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'in the presence of his friend', 64, 93, 'question', 'Friendship Dynamics', 'What does it mean to make commitments in front of friends? How does this verse challenge us to consider the nature of our relationships and the promises we make? Reflecting on the context of friendship in the Bible prompts us to evaluate the depth and integrity of our commitments.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'He loveth transgression that loveth strife:', 0, 43, 'connection', 'Strife and Transgression', 'This phrase connects with James 4:1, which asks, ''From whence come wars and fightings among you? Come they not hence, even of your lusts that war in your members?'' Both passages highlight how personal desires and transgressions can incite conflict. Understanding this connection emphasizes the destructive nature of sin and its impact on relationships.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 4:1", "description": "Explores the source of conflicts stemming from desires."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'and he that exalteth his gate seeketh destruction.', 44, 94, 'theology', 'Pride and Downfall', 'Many scholars believe that the act of exalting one''s gate symbolizes pride and a desire for status, which can lead to moral and spiritual destruction. This concept is echoed in Proverbs 16:18, ''Pride goeth before destruction, and a haughty spirit before a fall.'' The theological implication here is that humility is essential for a righteous life, contrasting with the folly of arrogance.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Proverbs 16:18", "description": "Discusses the relationship between pride and destruction."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'He loveth transgression that loveth strife:', 0, 43, 'question', 'Nature of Conflict', 'What does it reveal about our hearts when we find ourselves drawn to strife and conflict? How can we discern if our actions are rooted in a desire for righteousness or simply a love of transgression?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'and he that exalteth his gate seeketh destruction.', 44, 94, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Exalteth''', 'נָשָׂא (nasa, H5375) - to lift, carry, or take. This Hebrew term implies raising one''s status or position, which in this context can lead to one''s downfall when done out of pride. The choice to ''exalt'' oneself is often associated with a disregard for humility, thus leading to destruction.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5375", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term related to ''exalt''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'He that hath a froward heart findeth no good: ', 0, 46, 'connection', 'Froward Heart Connection', 'This phrase echoes the sentiment found in James 1:8, which states, ''A double-minded man is unstable in all his ways.'' Both verses highlight the instability and lack of good outcomes associated with a divided or froward heart. Understanding this connection emphasizes the biblical principle that moral integrity and a singular focus lead to a fruitful life.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 1:8", "description": "Highlights the instability of those with divided hearts."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'and he that hath a perverse tongue falleth into mischief.', 46, 103, 'theology', 'The Power of Speech', 'Many scholars believe this verse reflects the broader theological concept found in James 3:5-6 regarding the power of the tongue. The idea that speech can lead one into mischief aligns with the teaching that our words can either build up or destroy. This suggests a need for careful stewardship of our speech as a reflection of our inner character.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 3:5-6", "description": "Discusses the power and potential destructiveness of the tongue."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'falleth into mischief.', 81, 103, 'question', 'Reflection on Mischief', 'What does it mean for our words to lead us into mischief, and how can we guard against this in our daily conversations? Reflecting on this question can help us assess the impact of our speech and its alignment with our faith.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'He that hath a froward heart findeth no good: ', 0, 46, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Froward''', 'עִקְשֵׁי (iqesh, H6141) - froward, perverse. This Hebrew term suggests a stubborn and rebellious heart. Its use here underscores that such a disposition not only leads to negative outcomes but also signifies a deeper moral failing. The connection to one''s heart condition reflects the biblical teaching that the heart is the source of one''s actions.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H6141", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term meaning froward or perverse."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'He that begetteth a fool doeth it to his sorrow', 0, 47, 'connection', 'Parental Responsibility', 'This phrase echoes the sentiment found in Proverbs 10:1, which states, ''A wise son makes a glad father, but a foolish son is a sorrow to his mother.'' The connection emphasizes the profound emotional impact that a child''s foolishness can have on parents, highlighting the weight of parental responsibility in guiding children towards wisdom.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 10:1", "description": "Illustrates the emotional consequences of a child''s behavior on parents."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'the father of a fool hath no joy', 53, 85, 'theology', 'Impact of Foolishness', 'Many scholars believe that this verse reveals a theological principle about the relationship between wisdom and joy. The absence of joy in the life of a father with a foolish child may reflect the broader biblical theme that living in alignment with God''s wisdom brings fulfillment, while folly leads to sorrow and discontent. This underscores the importance of seeking wisdom, both for oneself and for one''s children.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'doeth it to his sorrow', 25, 47, 'greek', 'Meaning of Sorrow', 'סָבַל (sabal, H5445) - to bear, carry, or endure. This Hebrew term conveys a sense of deep emotional burden and distress, suggesting that the act of raising a fool results in significant sorrow for the father. The choice of this word highlights the weighty implications of foolishness not just on the individual, but on their family as well.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5445", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term used."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'the father of a fool hath no joy', 53, 85, 'question', 'Reflection on Parenting', 'What does it mean for a parent to find joy in their children, and how does this verse challenge you to reflect on the wisdom you impart to them? In what ways can you actively nurture wisdom within your family to avoid the sorrow mentioned here?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'A merry heart doeth good like a medicine', 0, 40, 'connection', 'Joy and Healing', 'This phrase connects with Nehemiah 8:10, which states, ''The joy of the Lord is your strength.'' Both verses emphasize the profound impact of joy on well-being. Joy is not just emotional but can have tangible effects on health and resilience, highlighting the holistic nature of human experience in Scripture.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Nehemiah 8:10", "description": "Joy is a source of strength and healing."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'but a broken spirit drieth the bones', 42, 78, 'theology', 'Spiritual State and Health', 'Many scholars believe this verse illustrates the connection between spiritual well-being and physical health. The idea that a ''broken spirit'' can lead to physical decline suggests a holistic view of humanity in biblical theology, where emotional and spiritual states directly affect physical health.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Proverbs 17:22", "description": "Explains the linkage between spirit and physical health."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'A merry heart doeth good like a medicine', 0, 40, 'question', 'Impact of Joy', 'What practical steps can you take to cultivate a ''merry heart'' in your daily life, considering its medicinal effects on your spirit and health?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'but a broken spirit drieth the bones', 42, 78, 'greek', 'Understanding ''broken spirit''', 'רָחוּץ (rachuts, H7356) - broken, crushed. This term conveys a deep sense of despair and emotional pain, indicating that a broken spirit can lead to significant suffering, both emotionally and physically.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H7356", "description": "Indicates the emotional state impacting physical health."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'A wicked man taketh a gift out of the bosom to pervert the ways of judgment.', 0, 76, 'connection', 'Corruption in Judgment', 'This verse resonates with Exodus 23:8, which warns against accepting bribes that can distort justice. Both passages highlight the corrupting power of gifts and the moral responsibility to uphold fairness in judgment. Understanding this connection emphasizes the biblical stance on integrity and the harmful effects of wickedness in leadership.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 23:8", "description": "A warning against bribes that pervert justice."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'A wicked man taketh a gift out of the bosom to pervert the ways of judgment.', 0, 76, 'theology', 'Moral Integrity', 'This passage suggests that moral integrity is foundational in leadership and community life. Many scholars believe that the act of accepting bribes not only undermines justice but also reflects a deeper spiritual malaise, where one''s character is compromised for personal gain. This highlights the biblical principle that righteousness is essential for societal well-being.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'A wicked man taketh a gift out of the bosom to pervert the ways of judgment.', 0, 76, 'question', 'Evaluating Our Choices', 'In what ways might we be tempted to compromise our integrity for personal benefit? How does this passage challenge us to reflect on our decisions and their impact on justice and fairness in our lives?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'A wicked man taketh a gift out of the bosom to pervert the ways of judgment.', 0, 76, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Wicked Man''', 'רָשָׁע (rasha, H7563) - wicked, guilty, criminal. This Hebrew term indicates a person who is not just morally wrong but actively opposes justice and righteousness. Its use here underscores the severity of the actions taken by such individuals, emphasizing the spiritual implications of their choices.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H7563", "description": "Strong''s number for ''wicked.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'Wisdom is before him that hath understanding', 0, 44, 'connection', 'Wisdom and Understanding', 'This phrase connects with Proverbs 2:6, which states, ''For the Lord gives wisdom; from his mouth come knowledge and understanding.'' The relationship highlights that true wisdom is a divine gift and is foundational for genuine understanding. The pursuit of wisdom leads to a deeper relationship with God and a clearer perspective on life.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 2:6", "description": "Emphasizes the divine source of wisdom."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'the eyes of a fool are in the ends of the earth', 50, 97, 'theology', 'Folly and Distraction', 'Many scholars believe that this verse illustrates the nature of folly as being fixated on worldly pursuits rather than spiritual insight. This aligns with the biblical theme of the ''fool'' who disregards God''s wisdom (Psalm 14:1). The ''ends of the earth'' metaphorically suggests a lack of focus, as fools chase after transient matters instead of eternal truths.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 14:1", "description": "Describes the folly of denying God."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'Wisdom is before him that hath understanding', 0, 44, 'question', 'Seeking Wisdom', 'What does it mean to have wisdom ''before'' you? How can this perspective shape your daily decisions and interactions with others? Reflect on the implications of actively pursuing wisdom and understanding in contrast to being distracted by the ''ends of the earth.''', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'the eyes of a fool are in the ends of the earth', 50, 97, 'greek', 'Foolishness in Perspective', 'נָבָל (naval, H5036) - fool, senseless person. This Hebrew term conveys a moral deficiency and lack of insight. It is significant in understanding the biblical portrayal of a fool as someone who is not just unwise but morally lacking, emphasizing the need for spiritual discernment.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5036", "description": "Indicates the Hebrew word for fool."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'A foolish son is a grief to his father', 0, 38, 'connection', 'Parental Grief Theme', 'This verse echoes the sentiment found in Proverbs 10:1, which states, ''A wise son makes a glad father, but a foolish son is the sorrow of his mother.'' The connection highlights the emotional weight that a child''s choices can bear on parents, emphasizing the duality of joy and grief in parental relationships. It serves as a reminder of the profound impact of wisdom and folly on familial bonds.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 10:1", "description": "Related verse emphasizing the impact of a child''s behavior on parental feelings."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'bitterness to her that bare him', 44, 75, 'theology', 'Value of Wisdom in Family', 'Many scholars believe this passage reflects the theological understanding of the family unit as a microcosm of society. The grief and bitterness experienced by parents due to a foolish child underscores the importance of instilling wisdom and righteousness. This aligns with the biblical principle that wisdom is foundational for a flourishing family life, as seen in Proverbs 1:8-9, which encourages children to heed parental instruction.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Proverbs 1:8-9", "description": "Verses that emphasize the significance of wisdom and parental guidance."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'A foolish son is a grief to his father', 0, 38, 'question', 'Impact of Actions on Relationships', 'How can the behavior of a child influence the emotional well-being of their parents? Reflecting on this verse prompts consideration of the responsibilities children carry in their relationships. What steps can one take to cultivate wisdom that honors and uplifts their family?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'A foolish son is a grief to his father', 0, 38, 'greek', 'Understanding ''foolish''', 'נָבָל (naval, H5036) - fool, wicked. This Hebrew term denotes not only a lack of wisdom but also a moral deficiency. The use of ''foolish'' in this context emphasizes the gravity of the son''s actions, suggesting that his choices lead to destructive consequences for the family unit, which is a recurrent theme in Proverbs.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5036", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word meaning ''foolish.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'Also to punish the just is not good, nor to strike princes for equity.', 0, 70, 'connection', 'Justice and Punishment', 'This verse echoes the sentiment found in Isaiah 5:23, which states, ''Who acquit the guilty for a bribe, but deny justice to the innocent.'' Both passages highlight the immorality of punishing the innocent and underscore the importance of fairness in justice. Understanding these connections helps us reflect on God''s standards for justice, where the just are protected and the guilty are held accountable.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Isaiah 5:23", "description": "Highlights the moral stance against unjust punishment."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'punish the just', 8, 23, 'theology', 'God''s Justice', 'This passage suggests a theological principle that God values justice and equity, which is foundational in Christian doctrine. Many scholars believe it reveals God''s character as just and righteous, emphasizing that He does not condone the punishment of the innocent. Such a understanding encourages believers to pursue justice in their own lives and communities, reflecting God''s nature.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'nor to strike princes for equity', 37, 69, 'question', 'Equity and Authority', 'What does it mean to strike princes for equity, and how does this reflect our understanding of authority and justice? Considering the implications of this phrase can lead us to examine how we perceive leaders in our society. Do we hold them to a standard of equity that aligns with God''s justice, or do we overlook their faults for the sake of their position?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'He that hath knowledge spareth his words:', 0, 41, 'connection', 'Wisdom in Speech', 'This phrase connects to Proverbs 10:19, which states, ''In the multitude of words there wanteth not sin: but he that refraineth his lips is wise.'' Both verses emphasize the importance of restraint in speech, highlighting that wisdom is often demonstrated through careful and measured words. This connection reinforces the idea that true knowledge leads to thoughtful communication.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 10:19", "description": "Proverbs emphasizes the wisdom of restraint in speech."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'and a man of understanding is of an excellent spirit.', 42, 95, 'theology', 'Spirit of Understanding', 'This passage suggests that possessing understanding not only enriches one''s intellect but also elevates one''s spirit. Many scholars believe this reflects the biblical concept that spiritual insight and character are intertwined, as seen in James 3:17, which describes wisdom from above as being pure, peaceable, and gentle. This highlights the transformative nature of true understanding.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "James 3:17", "description": "Describes the qualities of divine wisdom."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'He that hath knowledge spareth his words:', 0, 41, 'question', 'Reflection on Communication', 'How can we cultivate a habit of sparing our words in conversations? What might be the impact on our relationships and understanding if we practice restraint in our speech, as this verse suggests?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'Even a fool, when he holdeth his peace, is counted wise:', 0, 56, 'connection', 'Wisdom in Silence', 'This phrase connects with Job 13:5, where silence is implied as a wise response to suffering. It highlights the idea that sometimes refraining from speaking can demonstrate wisdom, especially in challenging situations. By choosing silence, one may avoid unnecessary conflict and show discernment.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Job 13:5", "description": "Job suggests that silence may be the wisest choice in difficult times."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'he that shutteth his lips is esteemed a man of understanding.', 61, 122, 'theology', 'Understanding through Restraint', 'Many scholars believe that this verse emphasizes the value of self-control and restraint in communication. It reflects the biblical principle that true understanding often involves listening more than speaking, aligning with James 1:19, which encourages believers to be ''quick to hear, slow to speak.''', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 1:19", "description": "James emphasizes listening over speaking as a sign of maturity."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'a fool, when he holdeth his peace, is counted wise:', 5, 56, 'question', 'Value of Silence', 'What does this passage suggest about the relationship between wisdom and silence in your own life? How can you practice restraint in your speech to cultivate a deeper understanding and wisdom?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 17, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'Even a fool, when he holdeth his peace, is counted wise:', 0, 56, 'greek', 'Key Greek Term', 'σοφός (sophos, G4680) - wise, skilled, having a deep understanding. This term highlights that wisdom is not solely about knowledge but also about the application of knowledge in one''s actions and words.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G4680", "description": "Strong''s number for the term ''wise.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 18, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'Through desire a man, having separated himself, seeketh and intermeddleth with all wisdom.', 0, 90, 'connection', 'Desire and Wisdom', 'The phrase ''Through desire a man'' connects with James 1:5, where it says, ''If any of you lacks wisdom, let him ask of God, who gives to all liberally.'' This highlights the importance of desire in seeking wisdom, suggesting that a sincere yearning for understanding is essential in the pursuit of divine knowledge.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 1:5", "description": "Encouragement to seek wisdom from God"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 18, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'Through desire a man, having separated himself, seeketh and intermeddleth with all wisdom.', 0, 90, 'theology', 'Separation for Wisdom', 'Many scholars believe that the act of separating oneself, as noted in this verse, reflects a necessary withdrawal from distractions in order to seek wisdom. This aligns with the Christian teaching that solitude can foster a deeper relationship with God and enhance one''s understanding of spiritual truths (see Matthew 6:6).', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 18, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'desire', 8, 14, 'greek', 'Desire in Hebrew', 'תַּאֲוָה (taavah, H8378) - desire, longing, craving. This term implies an intense yearning or strong wish, indicating that the pursuit of wisdom stems from deep inner desires.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8378", "description": "Strong''s number for Hebrew word for desire"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 18, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'having separated himself', 22, 46, 'question', 'Purpose of Separation', 'What does it mean to ''separate oneself'' in your pursuit of wisdom? How might this separation influence your understanding of God''s truth in your life?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 18, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'A fool hath no delight in understanding', 0, 39, 'connection', 'Foolishness in Scripture', 'This phrase connects to Psalm 14:1, which states, ''The fool says in his heart, “There is no God.”'' Both verses emphasize the folly of rejecting wisdom and understanding. Understanding is fundamentally tied to recognizing the divine, thus a fool''s rejection of understanding ultimately reflects a deeper spiritual blindness.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 14:1", "description": "Connection highlighting the biblical definition of a fool"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');